{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658051"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20700"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20700"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95813"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13576"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78592"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12435"},{"type":"tags","id":"12436"},{"type":"tags","id":"12577"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32614"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95813"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA homeless man is found unconscious in a park during winter with a core body temperature of 29\u00b0C. His extremities are cold, pale, and swollen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological mechanism of tissue injury in prolonged hypothermia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inflammatory cytokine release from damaged cells","Mitochondrial dysfunction from cold stress","Excessive vasodilation causing nutrient depletion","Direct crystallisation of water and indirect circulatory changes","Increased metabolic activity in peripheral tissues"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect crystallisation of water and indirect circulatory changes\u003C/strong\u003E. Hypothermia causes tissue injury through two main mechanisms: direct effects from physical disruption within cells by high salt concentrations caused by crystallisation of intracellular and extracellular water (as seen in frostbite), and indirect effects from circulatory changes that vary based on the rate and duration of temperature drop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory cytokine release from damaged cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While inflammation may occur as a secondary response to tissue damage, it is not the primary mechanism of injury in hypothermia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial dysfunction from cold stress\u003C/strong\u003E - While cellular metabolism is affected by cold temperatures, this is a consequence rather than the primary mechanism of tissue injury.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive vasodilation causing nutrient depletion\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because hypothermia typically causes vasoconstriction, not vasodilation. While alcohol consumption may cause initial vasodilation, prolonged cold exposure leads to vasoconstriction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased metabolic activity in peripheral tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because hypothermia actually decreases metabolic activity in tissues. Cold exposure triggers vasoconstriction to conserve core body heat, reducing metabolic activity in peripheral tissues.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn slow chilling, as might occur in trench foot, vasoconstriction and increased vascular permeability lead to oedema and hypoxia. With sudden, persistent chilling, vasoconstriction and increased blood viscosity cause ischaemic injury and degenerative changes in peripheral nerves. If ischaemia is prolonged, hypoxic changes and infarction of affected tissues can result in gangrene of extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hypothermia causes tissue injury through direct effects (crystallisation of water) and indirect effects (circulatory changes).","Slow chilling induces vasoconstriction and increased vascular permeability, leading to oedema and hypoxia.","Sudden persistent chilling causes vasoconstriction and increased blood viscosity, resulting in ischaemic injury and peripheral nerve damage.","Prolonged ischaemia from hypothermia can lead to hypoxic changes and infarction of affected tissues."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 428."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78592"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78592"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:28:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:30:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13576"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95813"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11657"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Environme